e=1> Well, I really dont think anyone should spend their money on this any time soon.  I read an interesting article on gamespy i think it was, and they were saying how because of the internet game companies dont create quality games like they used to, and they just release and patch later.  I think AO will be much like this, and i really dont buy the whole debug crap.  I dont think anyone should really buy it till about a month or 2 after its release because it will probably be pretty crazy with lag and all.  For those who cant wait i guess it's ok, but EQ and AC had the exact same problems (and in AC's case still has the same problem) and UO was pretty problematic as well, and AO really doesnt seem to be any different.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon2.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ukerryndarkwater.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kerryn Darkwater</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 329<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/22/01 3:29:12 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hmmmm</span><hr size=1> I hate VI just to give you some background but to answer Elwyn's question I will still be playing EQ and probably whining about how crap Verant are, if and only if, AO is totally crap. If its anywhere near as good as EQ then I'll go.<br>
<br>
I think you'll find that before Funcom goes live with AO it will be working properly and there won't be any significant lag. Sure there will be bugs but not majorly so.<br>
<br>
VI have had 2 years to iron out a lot of the bugs in their game I'll grant that fact. However im still waiting to see things that have needed fixing for 2 years that are simple 2 minute jobs. Verant lists them as working as intended (which lets face it is a poor excuse) or low priority. An example of which is buying multiple items at once which took in a lot of peoples opinion way too long for the amount of coding it required.<br>
<br>
Funcom have a larger staff base then VI. Which means if they prioritize tasks properly ( which every working person amongst us has to do on a dialy basis so why can't Verant ) they should iron out the bugs in half the time it took VI or less.<br>
<br>
Funcom are paying people to properly GM the game and run dynamic quests at a moments notice. According to Funcoms press release there won't be anyone turning up to tell you &quot;Im sorry, we can not help you with that&quot; or &quot;I do not have the power to help you with that&quot; Simply all guides and GMs will be empowered. ( This includes a properly phrased and publicized reimbursement policy that can't be paraphrased with &quot;We will not help you with anything&quot;<br>
<br>
I don't see this being Diablo II all over again. For one AO is a online role-playing game. Diablo II was a role playing game with an online feature. The two whilst seemingly similar are very different things. I do see a significant drop of EQ players when AO goes live and I'll tell you why.<br>
<br>
People want to get there and do things first. They do not want to get there when everyone else is way ahead of them. ( Incidentally, thats why we won't be getting the massive influx of players that Verant expects with SoL ) People will flock to a laggy/bugged game if need be just to make sure they get a head start on everyone else.<br>
<br>
After that the amount of EQ players will go up again as some people find that they just don't like AO full stop and will return to EverCamp. Then it will steadily fall.<br>
<br>
I promise you that within 6 months of AO going live VI will merge 2 servers and more will be on the cards. We would have seen this with Asherons Call if it wasn't so hopelessly bad.<br>
